Title : Candies Creek Ridge
Text : '''Candies Creek Ridge''', also known (more commonly in the past) as '''Clingan Ridge''', is a [[geographic feature]] [[ridge]] located primarily in [[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley County]], [[Tennessee]]. 
==Geography==
The ridge, one of a series of paralleling ridges that are a continuation of the [[Ridge-and-Valley Appalachians|Ridge-and-Valley]] [[Appalachian Mountains|Appalachians]], is one of the tallest, averaging approximately 997 feet (304 meters) of elevation.<ref name=satellite>{{cite web|website=satelliteview.com|url=http://www.satelliteview.co/?lid=4610958_US_TRDGE_TN&place=Candies-Creek-Ridge-TN |title=Candies Creek Ridge, TN}}</ref> The highest point, in [[Cleveland, Tennessee]], is 1,014 feet (309 meters).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nearbymountains.com/Ridge/TN/Candies%20Creek%20Ridge |title=Candies Creek Ridge, TN |website=Nearby Mountains}}</ref> It is also known as Lebanon Ridge south of Cleveland. The ridge stretches from [[Tunnel Hill, Georgia]] to the [[Hiwassee River]] at the Bradley/[[McMinn County, Tennessee|McMinn County]] line in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itouchmap.com/?d=1279492&s=TN&f=ridge|website=itouchmap.com|title=Candies Creek Ridge}}</ref> Several highways cross the formation including (from south to north) [[Georgia State Route 2|GA SR 2]], [[Tennessee State Route 317|TN SR 317]], [[APD-40]], [[U.S. Route 11|US 11]]/[[U.S. Route 64|US 64]], [[Tennessee State Route 312|SR 312]], [[Interstate 75]] and [[Tennessee State Route 60|SR 60]] (together), [[Sgt. Paul Huff Parkway|Paul Huff Parkway]], and [[Tennessee State Route 308|SR 308]].<ref name=satellite/>

==Nearby==
To the west is a ridge usually referred to in Tennessee as Mount Zion Ridge, and in the valley between the ridges in Tennessee is Candies Creek.<ref name=south/> To the east is a ridge referred to in northern Bradley County as Mouse Creek Ridge, and in the valley between is South Mouse Creek.<ref name=east>{{cite map|publisher=[[US Geological Survey]]|title=East Cleveland, Tennessee|url=https://ngmdb.usgs.gov/img4/ht_icons/Browse/TN/TN_East%20Cleveland_147460_1976_24000.jpg|year=1976|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> This ridge is called Lead Mine Ridge in the southern part of the Bradley County and in Georgia.<ref name=south>{{cite map|publisher=[[US Geological Survey]]|title=South Cleveland, Tennessee|url=https://ngmdb.usgs.gov/img4/ht_icons/Browse/TN/TN_South%20Cleveland_155743_1965_24000.jpg|year=1965|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{AASHTO minutes |year=1982A |page=2 |accessdate=January 24, 2015 |link=https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b5/AASHTO_USRN_1982-11-19.pdf}}</ref>

In Cleveland, the ridge has become a popular site for businesses and land development.{{cn|date=February 2016}}

==History==
[[File:Candy's creek mission historical marker.jpg|220px|thumb|right|A historical marker once stood along State Route 60 near the location of the Candy's Creek Cherokee Mission Station]]
Candies Creek, historically Candy's Creek, in the valley west of the ridge in Bradley County, was named for Henry Candy, who located along the creek after the Cherokee Treaty of 1817.<ref name=ross>"Horse and Saddle Days on Candies Creek in Bradley County, Tennessee." Ernest L. Ross. 1972.</ref> Prior to that it was called Little Kiuka Creek by the Cherokees.<ref name=ross/> The Candy's Creek Cherokee Indian Mission Station, organized in 1824 by [[Samuel Worcester]] and five others, stood along the creek a short distance north of the present day location of the intersection of SR 60 and Paul Huff Parkway.<ref>"Ref Red Clay and Rattlesnake Springs." James G. Corn. 1959.</ref> The station, which closed in 1838 after the [[Cherokee Removal]], has the distinction of being the first organized church and post office in Bradley County, and also contained a school.<ref name=banner16>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=May 3, 2016|title=Candyâ€™s Creek Cherokee Elementary to be name of new Cleveland school|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/candys-creek-cherokee-elementaryto-be-name-of-new-cleveland-school,33516|work=[[Cleveland Daily Banner]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-03-31}}</ref> A historical marker, commemorating the mission station was installed along SR 60 in 1959 near the present-day intersection of Paul Huff Parkway, and unknowingly disappeared, reportedly around the time Paul Huff Parkway was constructed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=April 5, 2016|title=Greenway chair, historians have elementary school site proposals|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/greenway-chair-historians-have-elementary-school-site-proposals,31451|work=Cleveland Daily Banner|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> An elementary school, set to open in August 2019, will be named for the mission station.<ref name=banner16/>

In Bradley County, the ridge is named for the Clingan family, who lived on it in what is now northern Cleveland.<ref>{{citeweb|website=drw.50webs.com|url=http://drw.50webs.com/norman/normcredits.html|title= Credits and Sources for Norman Genealogy}}</ref> A.A. Clingan, one of the family members, was Bradley County's first elected [[Sheriffs in the United States|sheriff]], serving from 1837 to 1838 and 1840 to 1846. The family of his wife, Martha Blythe, founded [[Blythe Ferry]] on the south side of the [[Tennessee River]] in [[Meigs County, Tennessee]] 1809. The Clingan family cemetery, located on the western foot of the ridge off of SR 60, was rediscovered in 2014 and restored in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=June 14, 2016|title=Cleaning up the family past|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/cleaning-up-the-family-past,36368|work=[[Cleveland Daily Banner]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee |access-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref>

